sect2.para:
It cannot be overstated that one important purpose of the interview is to develop rapport with the patient. Rapport serves as the foundation upon which all clinical work is completed (also see Chap.

               1

         ). If the clinician does not have rapport with the patient, then the interview may be unsuccessful in obtaining necessary information. Fortunately, most psychologists are well-skilled in establishing rapport with patients. Some things should be done at the start with a patient in order to establish rapport, and the first meeting with the patient is critical in this regard. Patients should be greeted with a smile and welcomed to the clinic. They should know that their comfort is a priority; for example, they should be informed where the restroom is, and offered a drink of water. Clinicians may wish to keep snacks on hand so patients do not feel hungry. Some clinics offer coffee and tea to patients, but other clinics avoid this in order to set firmer boundaries with patients. Efforts should be made to have frequent eye contact with the patient, and it can be helpful to share a laugh at least once. It can be helpful to clinicians to find something they have in common with a patient and to point that out to the patient. This can be a place in common where they have both lived (without discussing where the clinician currently lives), a favorite pastime, favorite restaurant, favorite sports team, or other commonality that can be discussed without crossing professional boundaries. Even though brief, this time spent leads to development of rapport, which is the basis of all clinical work.

Neuropsychologists typically start the interview with general, open-ended questions (e. g., “so what brings you here today?) and gradually move toward specific questions (Donders,
            2022
         ). This method allows the examiner to observe how the patient reacts to ambiguous stimuli and how the patient structures an unclear situation. Valuable behavioral observations can be made, such as the patient’s ability to find words when communicating freely, their ability to stay on topic, ability to respond to your needs, etc. This also gives the patient the opportunity to express certain needs, problems, or concerns that are most important to them (e. g., an older adult saying “My daughter is trying to put me in a home” or “My memory is shot and I just know I’ve got Alzheimer’s disease,” or a younger adult saying “I really want to be able to go back to work” vs. “I am unable to work and I’m trying to get disability compensation”). This gives the examiner valuable insight into the patient’s thought processes. As the interview proceeds, the clinician can probe for details into relevant areas and ask about areas that have not been covered.

Some clinicians prefer to interview the patient without having any caregivers in the room, whereas others interview the patient and caregiver simultaneously. It is certainly important to get information from both parties, but each method has its strengths and weaknesses. If the patient is interviewed alone, it is possible that their cognitive impairments or motivations will lead them to report information that is inaccurate, and the clinician may not realize this. This can be ameliorated by interviewing a caregiver at a different time and checking for accuracy. Sometimes, for reasons of practicality, the patient and caregiver are interviewed together. Donders (
            2022
         ) points out that in this case, care must be taken to allow the patient to answer questions independently without being interrupted by the caregiver. The clinician must also show that the patient’s opinions are valued as much as, if not more than, those of the caregiver. Many clinicians make the mistake of speaking primarily to the caregiver, seeming to ignore the patient in the room. This practice, which can be disrespectful to the patient, can lead the patient to feel unimportant or untrustworthy and thus interfere with rapport. On the other hand, the patient may defer to their caregiver and make little effort to provide their own answer. Here, the clinician should also make efforts to encourage the patient to provide their own opinion on things.

With regard to neuropsychological assessment, the ethical standards of the American Psychological Association (American Psychological Association,
            2017
         ) assert the importance of providing services to the patient in a language consistent with the patient’s preference and reported language proficiency. Using a language that the patient understands allows the patient to be able to make an informed decision about consenting to the assessment. Best practice consists of using an interpreter that is accredited and an interpreter that can come to the evaluation in-person versus via telephone or video services (Fujii et al., 
            2022
         ). On the day of the interview, the patient must give consent to using an interpreter for the assessment and confirm that they understand the interpreter that is present. The clinician then prepares with the interpreter first. Factors of consideration that are emphasized in this pre-interview discussion include, but are not limited to, reviewing and/or defining terms, reviewing the importance of relaying as exact as possible translations of the patient’s responses back to the clinician, as well as informing the interpreter that patients may have difficulty with communication. At the start of the interview, time should be spent preparing the patient for what to expect when using an interpreter in an interview. The clinician will benefit from speaking in short clear sentences and with a slower rate of speech. At times, repetition or re-explanation of questions or words will assist with the patient’s understanding of questions presented. At the end of the interview, the clinician should also provide an overall summary of the patient’s responses to allow an opportunity for the clinician to ensure that they understood the patient. Following the interview, discussion with the interpreter one-on-one is again recommended for review of the patient’s responses.

Importantly, other aspects of a patient’s culture need to be attended to in addition to the patient’s language proficiency. A helpful acronym has been developed and suggested by Fujii (
            2018
         ) to aid in this process: ECLECTIC. The components of the acronym ECLECTIC include Education, Culture (including acculturation), Language, Economics, Communication style, factors related to a Testing situation, conceptualization of Intelligence, and Context of immigration. Further reading on these topics is recommended (Fujii, 
            2018
         ).

Interviews with patients suspected of having dementia should start with assessing the patient’s knowledge of the reason for referral, as outlined before. The interview should also include discussion of specific cognitive difficulties the patient or their caregiver has noticed. This should start by asking the patient what sort of problems they have been experiencing. Clinicians should probe for examples of cognitive difficulties, which can be very informative. The caregiver may provide a response such as “well, for example, yesterday he asked me five times if I’ve paid the electric bill.” If the caregiver is unable to explain what difficulties the patient is having, or to generate examples, one helpful way to elucidate this information is to ask “Let’s say you had to leave town for a few days. Would you feel safe leaving your loved one at home alone?” This often can lead the caregiver to give specific examples of the patient’s difficulties. For example, this may lead the caregiver to say “No, there’s no way I could leave him home alone. He would forget to turn the stove off and to take his medications!” If the patient or caregiver cannot independently generate examples of everyday problems, then the neuropsychologist can offer examples to see if the patient shows these problems. Examples of everyday manifestations of cognitive problems can be gleaned from the Everyday Cognition Scale by Farias et al. (
            2008
         ).

Neuropsychologists are often requested to evaluate whether an older adult is experiencing symptoms of depression or dementia, or both. It is important to know that depression and dementia frequently co-occur, particularly in the early stages of dementia (Segal et al.,
            2018
         ). During the interview, several factors can help to differentiate between depression and dementia. Older adults with depressive symptoms are often aware of memory problems, or even exaggerate problems that may not even be present. Patients with dementia, on the other hand, are often unaware of their cognitive difficulties. Another obvious but important thing to assess is current and past history of depressive symptoms. This can help elucidate whether current depressive symptoms are contributing to cognitive impairment.

The clinician should ensure that the interview is ended appropriately. Donders (
            2022
         ) points out that it is often useful to summarize the main concerns noted in the interview, assess for correctness with the patient, and then ask the patient if there are any other questions or concerns the patient would like to add before proceeding with the evaluation. One benefit to this is that the patient may mention something that the clinician may have neglected to inquire into. Clinicians should also expect that there will be questions they forgot to ask, and these questions can be asked later in the evaluation, or even over the phone on a later date.
